ApplicationSubmissionInfoGrp.FormAndInfoAndMaterialsTxt: MOST OF THE FOUNDATION'S GRANTS TRADITIONALLY HAVE BEEN MADE THROUGH NATIONAL PROGRAMS ESTABLISHED TO ADDRESS SPECIFIC ISSUES IN HEALTH AND HEALTH CARE. THESE ISSUES AND TOPICS OF INTEREST ARE DESCRIBED ON THE FOUNDATION'S INTERNET SITE (WWW.RWJF.ORG). THE COMPETITIVE GRANT APPLICATION PROCESS FOR NATIONAL PROGRAMS BEGINS WITH A "CALL FOR PROPOSAL," WHICH CAN BE FOUND ON THE FOUNDATION'S INTERNET SITE. THE FOUNDATION ALSO AWARDS GRANTS OUTSIDE OF ITS NATIONAL PROGRAMS THAT MAY BE UNSOLICITED OR SOLICITED BY THE FOUNDATION, BUT THAT GENERALLY EITHER FIT THE FOUNDATION'S EXPLICIT FIELDS OF INTEREST WITHIN HEALTH AND HEALTH CARE, OR ADVANCE THE FOUNDATION'S OVERARCHING GOAL OF BUILDING A "CULTURE OF HEALTH" IN AMERICA. APPLICANTS MAY INITIATE THE GRANT PROCESS BY SUBMITTING A THREE-PAGE, ELECTRONIC BRIEF PROPOSAL USING THE APPLICATION FORM PROVIDED ON-LINE.
ApplicationSubmissionInfoGrp.SubmissionDeadlinesTxt: NO DEADLINES, EXCEPT WHEN FOUNDATION ISSUES A CALL FOR PROPOSAL (CFP). EACH CFP SPECIFIES THE TIMETA
ApplicationSubmissionInfoGrp.RestrictionsOnAwardsTxt: THE ROBERT WOOD JOHNSON FOUNDATION'S MISSION IS TO IMPROVE THE HEALTH AND HEALTH CARE OF ALL AMERICANS AND TO BUILD A CULTURE OF HEALTH THROUGHOUT THE COUNTRY - ENABLING ALL IN OUR DIVERSE SOCIETY TO LEAD HEALTHY LIVES, NOW AND FOR GENERATIONS TO COME. TO HELP AMERICANS LEAD HEALTHIER LIVES AND GET THE CARE THEY NEED, THE FOUNDATION MAKES GRANTS TO IDENTIFY AND PURSUE NEW OPPORTUNITIES TO ADDRESS PERSISTENT HEALTH CHALLENGES AND TO ANTICIPATE/RESPOND TO EMERGING CHALLENGES. FOR MANY YEARS, THE FOUNDATION HAS FOCUSED THE MAJORITY OF ITS GRANT MAKING IN SPECIFIC FIELDS SUCH AS HEALTH CARE COVERAGE, CHILDHOOD OBESITY, PUBLIC HEALTH, AND IMPROVING THE VALUE OF HEALTH CARE. GeneralExplanationGrp.MediumExplanationTxt: General Outreach and Support - Programs which support improving health care value, promoting prevention, growing the field of health and health care leadership, supporting communications and policy projects, and synthesizing and spreading research and evaluation findings through the web, social media and other means. $7,513,524 Access to Health Care Coverage - Programs, projects and activities that advance public awareness of health insurance coverage issues and the economic effects of health reform, provide data analysis of state and national-level coverage issues, and promote enrollment information and assistance to children and their families eligible for financial subsidies. $7,313,624 Advancing Change Leadership - Programs and activities to prepare health professionals for leadership; train scholars to conduct health policy and systems research; encourage youth to pursue health careers; enhance the skills and careers of frontline health workers; and promote diversity in the health workforce to serve the needs of a changing population. Includes programs to improve patient care and community health by reinforcing the role of nurses in hospital and ambulatory settings and in public health systems; to increase and improve inter-professional collaboration between nurses and other health professionals; reduce the nationwide nursing shortage and increase production of nursing faculty to meet growing demands for well-trained nurses. $6,649,061 Value - Programs to ensure that people have the information and support they need to make the best choices and get the care that's right for them; that the health care system is designed around the people it serves; and that public health departments are able to effectively and efficiently promote and protect the health of the people in the communities they serve. $5,743,010 Other Targeted Programs - Programs to revitalize public health systems, services and policies that protect, promote, and preserve the health of all Americans; to improve the quality and value of health care; to reduce childhood obesity; to support and strengthen vulnerable children and families; to catalyze demand for healthy places and practices; to bridge the concepts of health and health care; to achieve health equity; to create and promote innovations that may result in solutions at the cutting edge of health and health care; to find innovative ideas from other countries that could help improve our health here at home; to support locally-based projects that promote the health and health care of New Jerseyans; and to support research, evaluation, learning and communications efforts that can improve the nation's health. $23,432,142 Total Direct Charitable Activities: $50,651,361
